    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 333216,
      "reputation" : 6389,
      "user_id" : 658957,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 83,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/620df7466bff8f00deaf0c0a1e5aa006?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "enkara",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/658957/enkara"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 320,
    "last_activity_date" : 1436293128,
    "last_edit_date" : 1436293128,
    "creation_date" : 1429271863,
    "answer_id" : 29698543,
    "question_id" : 12893995,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In order to get all the details I had to add the -v option to romaintaz answer:</p>\n\n<pre><code>keytool -v -list -keystore &lt;FileName&gt;.keystore\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1108034,
      "reputation" : 583,
      "user_id" : 1099017,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 71,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ca7e1303e9ee5f868872ce5a47ab4b63?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Svetoslav",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1099017/svetoslav"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 29,
    "last_activity_date" : 1478001161,
    "creation_date" : 1478001161,
    "answer_id" : 40359515,
    "question_id" : 12893995,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>In a bash-like environment you can use:</p>\n\n<pre><code>keytool -list -v -keystore cacerts.jks | grep 'Alias name:' | grep -i foo\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>This command consist of 3 parts. As stated above, the <strong>1st</strong> part will list all trusted certificates with all the details and that's why the <strong>2nd</strong> part comes to filter only the alias information among those details. And finally in the <strong>3rd</strong> part you can search for a specific alias (or part of it). The <em>-i</em> turns the case insensitive mode on. Thus the given command will yield all aliases containing the pattern 'foo', f.e. foo, 123_FOO, fooBar, etc. For more information <code>man grep</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "comments" : [ {
      "owner" : {
